161
00:09:45,158 --> 00:09:49,419
Yeah, I just wanted to hear what you guys, what you thought and what you would prefer, I guess.

162
00:09:50,360 --> 00:09:57,361
Should we, if Todd is going to join, I think we did send the plans around to the email list.

163
00:09:57,461 --> 00:10:09,585
So I think we have basically had a chance to see it, but do we want to wait on that until Todd is here or we can have the document up on the screen?

164
00:10:12,035 --> 00:10:13,356
Yeah, I guess so, yeah.

165
00:10:13,457 --> 00:10:22,745
I mean, I can kind of remember what was discussed, but it would be, or I can run and pull it up for myself.

166
00:10:23,506 --> 00:10:34,956
Yeah, so I actually, I should say that I do have a, I took a stab at what I think might help solve the problem that I think you guys were having, but again, since I didn't hear it straight from you guys, I wanted to just

167
00:10:35,938 --> 00:10:37,219
Talk through it with you for a second.

168
00:10:39,100 --> 00:10:48,107
What I remember was the concern was how the bike lane ends and what the merge area looks like.

169
00:10:49,996 --> 00:11:08,028
And that it ends at a, and then the lane markings, there was some confusion because they're drawn onto the plans, but those are not, like the left straight and the right turn lanes, those are not part of the project.

170
00:11:09,709 --> 00:11:12,090
So there was some confusion about how it,

171
00:11:12,991 --> 00:11:16,814
interfaces with those that are not actually going to necessarily be there.

172
00:11:16,834 --> 00:11:25,442
I remember one point was when the bike lane basically shares space with the bus stop.

173
00:11:26,083 --> 00:11:34,049
I know it's common to paint the bike lane on the right-hand half of the bus stop and the left-hand half of the bus stop becomes a buffer.

174
00:11:35,691 --> 00:11:41,297
I think it's preferable to swap those, so put the bike lane painted on the left-hand side of the bus stop.

175
00:11:42,258 --> 00:11:51,447
The reason being that shortly after that, the bike lane ends, so cyclists then have to merge into the regular flow of traffic.

176
00:11:52,508 --> 00:11:56,392
Not to mention that I always think it looks a little awkward to paint

177
00:11:57,248 --> 00:12:05,353
a bike lane on the right-hand side of the bus stop, because then it encourages people to be on the right-hand side of a bus that's going to be letting passengers on and off.

178
00:12:07,454 --> 00:12:10,196
And that was one comment.

179
00:12:10,236 --> 00:12:16,719
And then also just how that interfaced with the turn lanes after that.

180
00:12:16,859 --> 00:12:20,321
But I think there was some confusion about whether those turn lanes are actually really there.

181
00:12:20,341 --> 00:12:25,564
Yeah, so because the Bellsway is a DCR road,

182
00:12:26,995 --> 00:12:35,119
we would have to go through a process with them in order to strike those lanes that way, or add anything to the approach.

183
00:12:36,260 --> 00:12:41,583
And that was, yeah, a mistake not supposed to be included in the package that was sent out.

184
00:12:42,643 --> 00:12:43,684
So that was our bad.

185
00:12:43,804 --> 00:12:49,387
But as far as the bus stop is concerned, excuse me, maybe it's confusing.

186
00:12:49,947 --> 00:12:51,748
So I've been using, I don't know,

187
00:12:52,812 --> 00:12:57,533
a standard that I pulled from VTD from the City of Boston Transportation Department.

188
00:12:58,394 --> 00:13:08,136
And actually it's not so much putting the bike lane on the right side, it's actually just the bike lane and the bus stop are the same space for that stretch for the length of the bus stop.

189
00:13:08,556 --> 00:13:11,137
That's something they've been using and it's one of their standard details.

190
00:13:12,037 --> 00:13:18,539
But if it's confusing, like that's obviously it's not our standard, so we don't necessarily have to use it if you all find it confusing.

191
00:13:19,439 --> 00:13:21,460
I think it is a new standard of theirs, so it might be

192
00:13:22,288 --> 00:13:23,188
PB, Lisa Smith-Miyazaki, she-her, hers.

193
00:13:37,555 --> 00:13:52,397
like to the left of parked cars, and then the bus stop takes up an area that doesn't have any parked cars, then the bike lane moves against the curb during that area instead of just continuing in a straight line.

194
00:13:53,338 --> 00:14:02,645
And that to me encourages, you know, if somebody is just following the bike lane as painted, they're much more likely to be in between that bus and that curb.

195
00:14:02,665 --> 00:14:15,193
And there's, and, you know, of course, you don't have to be, you don't have to do what the paint says, but it seems like it encourages people to be in the wrong place when a bus is letting off passengers.

196
00:14:18,665 --> 00:14:20,386
And it is what they do in other places.

197
00:14:20,786 --> 00:14:24,067
And I've seen that before.

198
00:14:24,207 --> 00:14:27,148
It doesn't look like it makes sense to me.

199
00:14:28,609 --> 00:14:31,210
Maybe there's another logic to why they do it that way.

200
00:14:31,290 --> 00:14:36,971
I suspect it's just because people think, oh, the bike lane needs to always be as far to the right as possible.

201
00:14:37,032 --> 00:14:40,833
And if there's room for a buffer between the bike lane and traffic, then it should be there.

202
00:14:41,894 --> 00:14:52,108
And that's not a bad way to think about it, except that in this case, I think it just encourages if it encourages people to do anything it encourages people to do the wrong thing.

203
00:14:52,129 --> 00:14:53,651
I think there's also.

204
00:14:55,742 --> 00:15:23,772
There's a little bit of variation and I'm not quite sure what the standard that we're talking about says in terms of how the bike lane enters the shared stop, because you can have, if the bike lane is like coming up to the bus stop, which is wider than the bike lane, it can either go up to the far right edge of the bus stop, or it can, you know, line up with the left edge.

205
00:15:24,750 --> 00:15:30,375
just, you know, not in terms of the markings within the bus stop, but the markings up to the bus stop and after the bus stop.

206
00:15:33,899 --> 00:15:35,460
And that can make a difference.

207
00:15:35,920 --> 00:15:38,803
Yeah, I think that's, that's kind of what we're.

208
00:15:38,823 --> 00:15:38,903
Yeah.

209
00:15:43,029 --> 00:15:43,930
Okay, Ernie.

210
00:15:43,950 --> 00:15:44,270
Gotcha.

211
00:15:44,711 --> 00:15:45,031
Yeah.

212
00:15:45,432 --> 00:15:49,316
In addition to the displeasure of being right hooked by a bus.

213
00:15:50,397 --> 00:16:04,571
Once we get critical mass of bike riders attempting to pass a bus on the right, it will become an incredible imperilment of discharged passengers, especially elder

214
00:16:05,502 --> 00:16:12,604
elderly or those in physical need to be having to look for bicycles coming as they exit a bus.

215
00:16:12,665 --> 00:16:13,745
I mean, that's a nightmare.

216
00:16:13,785 --> 00:16:15,145
And I agree with Emily there.

217
00:16:15,445 --> 00:16:20,987
We're just not seeing it yet because the numbers don't support that kind of hazard awareness.

218
00:16:21,708 --> 00:16:31,191
But yeah, we've got to keep the bikes in the left side of the bus and just engineer, if necessary, a successful and slow enough and carefully marked enough

219
00:16:31,711 --> 00:16:36,655
scissor intersection so that those lanes can interchange as necessary.

220
00:16:37,195 --> 00:16:45,181
Well, I think even if we can't, like if the bus stop overlaps with the bike lane, that's a common thing around here.

221
00:16:45,881 --> 00:16:53,406
But the bike lane doesn't need to change direction and go swerve up against the curb in that spot.

222
00:16:53,907 --> 00:16:57,730
It can just stay in a straight line, which effectively means that

223
00:16:58,450 --> 00:17:02,892
the bike lane aligns with the left edge of the bus stop, not with the right edge.

224
00:17:03,412 --> 00:17:06,614
And they do tend to paint it to align with the curb instead.

225
00:17:06,634 --> 00:17:14,118
And that's what I think is more likely to indicate to people that they should be on that right edge.

226
00:17:14,158 --> 00:17:17,559
And that's more likely that they're going to be in the way of passengers getting on and off.

227
00:17:18,059 --> 00:17:22,662
And I don't know why they don't just, you can just paint the bike lane going straight.

